B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                  FY 2024    FY 2025      FY 2026

Beginning in FY 2026, this program will be funded in PE 0602025E, Project MSL-01.

FY 2025 Plans:
- Evaluate prototype feasibility of previously developed extended optimized night vision designs.
- Demonstrate novel material testing techniques to generate design-relevant properties 10x faster than current approaches.
- Perform critical function and full system level demonstrations on material testing platforms and design optimization routines.
- Evaluate novel multimaterial designs to quantify performance, cost, and sustainability benefits.
- Develop hybrid additive manufacturing approaches to enable embedded structural health monitoring for load-bearing metallic
components without affecting structural performance.
- Develop detailed design and complete hardware-informed critical design review for a 0.5 meter-scale (effective aperture) liquid
mirror telescope system that will be capable of astronomical and SSA observations without spin-stabilization and that can be
scaled to larger apertures than readily (in terms of both cost and schedule) accessible by traditional (current) telescope build/
fabrication processes.
- Conduct out-of-plane liquid mirror hardware demonstration and begin advancing designs from laboratory setting to on-sky
demonstrations.
- Demonstrate and characterize compact, highly sensitive atomic vapor-based electric and magnetic field sensor devices.
- Demonstrate and characterize compact vapor-based quantum device with high atom-photon interaction strength and quantum
coherence.
- Explore the design space for metamaterial-based nanoelectronic device architectures for applications to quantum sensing,
computing, and communications.
- Explore and developed device-level fabrication techniques to incorporate functionally engineered quantum materials within
nanoelectronic device architectures.
- Perform preliminary materials and device characterization of metamaterial-based nanoelectronic devices to validate material-
scale and device-scale models of enhanced quantum effects.
FY 2025 to FY 2026 Increase/Decrease Statement:
The FY 2026 decrease reflects the transfer of the program from this PE/Project to PE 0602025E, Project MSL-01.
Title: Chemical Processing for Force Protection                                                                                        22.043     27.964              -
