Note
The fiscal year (FY) 2026 request for Ballistic Missile Defense (BMD) Enabling Programs includes $646.0 million of discretionary and $81.0 million of mandatory
(reconciliation) for a total of $727.0 million. The mandatory (reconciliation) funds provide for the initiation of Golden Dome for America requirements, including
specialized integrated architecture, system-of-systems engineering, modeling and simulation (M&S), and the establishment of a National Integrated Air and Missile
Defense (IAMD) Center, which implements the Virtual Warfare Center concept. Further information for this reconciliation request is provided in Section 20003 (Missile
Defense) of the Reconciliation Exhibit. Increase in discretionary funds provide a dedicated lab to support integration, evaluation, and refinement of Joint Tactical
Integrated Fire Control infrastructure.

A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
The Missile Defense System Enabling Programs provide critical products and processes needed to combine element missile defense capabilities into a single,
integrated, and layered System to counter existing threats and provide new defensive capabilities against emerging threats. Specifically, the Enabling Programs:


